nterpretations of familiar episodes while delving deep into the archives to uncover a much fuller picture of the era. Analyzing these sources, Isaiah Gruber argues that the business activity of monasteries played a significant role in the origins and course of the Troubles and that frequent changes in power forced Church ideologues to innovate politically, for example inventing new justifications for power to be granted to the people and to royal women. These new ideas, Gruber contends, ultimately helped bring about a new age in Russian spiritual life and a crystallization of the national mentality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aChurch and statezRussiaxHistoryy17th century. 0aOrthodox Eastern monasteriesxEconomic aspectszRussiaxHistoryy17th century. 4aHistory. 4aReligious Studies. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Orthodox.2bisacsh  aOrthodox Church ideologues, Russian spiritual life, post-Soviet religion in Russia.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150175738940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501757389423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501757389/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK